                      <td class="px-3 py-2">Over $551,350</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <p>
                For 2025, the calculator uses the same thresholds as an
                estimate. Congress can change tax law, so always verify current
                brackets with the IRS.
              </p>

              <h3>Formula used for long-term capital gains tax</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Net long-term gains:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Net LT gain} = \max\bigl(0,\ \text{LT gains} -
                  \text{LT losses} - \text{LT carryover}\bigr) \]
                </p>

                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Step 2 – Optional short-term netting (simplified):</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Net ST gain} = \text{ST gains} - \text{ST losses} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  If Net ST gain &lt; 0, up to \$3,000 of the loss can offset
                  ordinary income.
                </p>

                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Step 3 – Total taxable income including long-term
                    gain:</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Taxable income} = \text{Ordinary taxable income
                  (adjusted)} + \text{Net LT gain} \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>Step 4 – Apply LTCG brackets:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \(B_0\) and \(B_{15}\) be the top of the 0% and 15%
                  brackets for your filing status.
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Amount at 0\%} = \max\bigl(0,\ \min(B_0 -
                  \text{Ordinary},\ \text{Net LT gain})\bigr) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Amount at 15\%} = \max\bigl(0,\ \min(B_{15} -
                  \text{Ordinary} - \text{Amount at 0\%},\ \text{Net LT gain} -
                  \text{Amount at 0\%})\bigr) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Amount at 20\%} = \text{Net LT gain} - \text{Amount
                  at 0\%} - \text{Amount at 15\%} \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>Total long-term capital gains tax:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LT tax} = 0\% \cdot A_0 + 15\% \cdot A_{15} + 20\%
                  \cdot A_{20} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>What counts as a long-term capital gain?</h2>
              <p>
                In the U.S., a <strong>long-term capital gain</strong> is profit
                from selling a capital asset you held for
                <strong>more than one year</strong> (more than 12 months).
                Common examples:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Stocks, ETFs, mutual funds</li>
                <li>Real estate (not your primary home exclusion portion)</li>
                <li>Bonds, options, and other investments</li>
                <li>
                  Business interests and certain collectibles (though
                  collectibles can have different maximum rates)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you held the asset for <strong>one year or less</strong>, the
                gain is usually <strong>short-term</strong> and taxed at your
                ordinary income tax rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Key differences: long-term vs. short-term capital gains</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Holding period:</strong> More than one year vs. one
                  year or less.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax rate:</strong> Long-term gains get preferential
                  0%, 15%, or 20% rates; short-term gains are taxed at ordinary
                  income rates (up to 37% federally).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Planning flexibility:</strong> You can often choose
                  when to realize long-term gains to manage your tax bracket.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Strategies to reduce long-term capital gains tax</h2>
              <p>
                Here are common, IRS-recognized strategies investors use to
                manage capital gains tax:
              </p>
              <h3>1. Hold investments for more than one year</h3>
              <p>
                Simply extending your holding period beyond 12 months can move a
                gain from short-term to long-term, often cutting the tax rate
                significantly.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Tax-loss harvesting</h3>
              <p>Sell investments with losses to offset gains:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Long-term losses first offset long-term gains.</li>
                <li>Excess losses can offset the other type of gains.</li>
                <li>
                  Up to <strong>$3,000</strong> of net capital loss per year can
                  offset ordinary income, with the rest carried forward.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Be aware of the <strong>wash-sale rule</strong> for
                substantially identical securities (applies to losses, not
                gains).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Spread large sales across multiple years</h3>
              <p>
                If a single large sale would push you into the 20% bracket,
                consider:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Selling part at the end of one year and part at the beginning
                  of the next.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Coordinating with years when your ordinary income is lower
                  (e.g., early retirement, sabbatical).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Use tax-advantaged accounts</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>401(k), traditional IRA:</strong> Gains are
                  tax-deferred; withdrawals are taxed as ordinary income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Roth IRA:</strong> Qualified withdrawals are tax-free,
                  including gains.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HSAs and other accounts:</strong> May also offer tax
                  advantages depending on use.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>5. Consider the home sale exclusion</h3>
              <p>
                If you sell your primary residence and meet ownership and use
                tests, you may exclude up to <strong>$250,000</strong> of gain
                (<strong>$500,000</strong> if married filing jointly). Only the
                remaining gain is subject to capital gains tax.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This calculator focuses on
                  <strong>federal long-term capital gains tax</strong> for most
                  assets.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> model:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Collectibles (up to 28% maximum rate)</li>
                    <li>Unrecaptured Section 1250 gain (up to 25%)</li>
                    <li>Net investment income tax (NIIT) 3.8% surtax</li>
                    <li>Alternative minimum tax (AMT)</li>
                    <li>State and local income or capital gains taxes</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tax law changes frequently; always confirm current brackets
                  and rules with the IRS or a tax professional.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What are the 2024–2025 long-term capital gains tax rates?</h3>
              <p>
                For most assets, the U.S. federal long-term capital gains tax
                rates are <strong>0%</strong>, <strong>15%</strong>, or
                <strong>20%</strong>, depending on your taxable income and
                filing status. High-income taxpayers may also owe the 3.8% net
                investment income tax on top of these rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I pay capital gains tax if I don’t sell?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Capital gains tax is generally owed only when you
                <strong>realize</strong> a gain by selling or otherwise
                disposing of the asset. Unrealized gains (paper gains) are not
                taxed under current U.S. rules.
              </p>

              <h3>Are dividends taxed as capital gains?</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Qualified dividends</strong> are taxed at the same 0%,
                15%, or 20% rates as long-term capital gains, but they are
                reported separately. <strong>Nonqualified dividends</strong> are
                taxed at ordinary income rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator enough to file my taxes?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an educational planning tool. It does not replace
                IRS forms, official instructions, or professional tax advice.
                Use it to explore scenarios, then rely on official IRS guidance
                or a tax professional when filing.
              </p>
